            content: "<p>Portugal's government officially approved the 2026 State Budget with total expenditure reaching €140.25 billion ($153.14 billion), a 4.5% increase compared to the previous year's expenditure of €134.17 billion ($146.5 billion). This budget places housing as one of the top priorities of state fiscal policy, responding to the worsening housing affordability crisis across Portugal.</p><p>Portugal's economy is projected to grow 2% in 2026, increasing to 2.3% the following year, a target deemed realistic by most economists given the country's solid growth trend in recent years. The housing budget allocation includes rental subsidies for low-income families, incentives for affordable housing construction, and an accelerated construction permit program to address the housing supply shortage that is at the root of the crisis.</p><p>Tax changes in this budget also target the property sector, with several tax reliefs for first-time home buyers and tightened rules on speculative property investment believed to have contributed to soaring home prices in major cities like Lisbon and Porto.</p><p>Although the budget passed relatively smoothly compared to previous political drama, economists warn that Portugal's structural housing crisis challenges — including demographic imbalances and surging demand from foreign investors and digital nomads — require much deeper long-term reforms than mere annual budget adjustments.</p>",
